  <!--
    TYPE 3 CLINICAL INFORMATION BEST PRACTICES
    A Type 3 ePI introduces machine-readable clinical data structures representing 
    the rules set forth in the narrative sections (e.g. indications, contraindications, dosages).
  -->

  <!-- 
    KEY CONCEPT: The Granularity Rule
    
    Each discrete clinical concept gets its own ClinicalUseDefinition resource.
    Do NOT combine multiple indications, contraindications, or warnings into a 
    single resource. This one-concept-per-resource pattern enables precise machine 
    queries (e.g., "find all products contraindicated in hepatic impairment") and 
    mirrors the granularity expected by clinical decision support systems.
  -->

  <!-- 
    KEY CONCEPT: The Five ClinicalUseDefinition Types
    
    FHIR provides five distinct ClinicalUseDefinition types, each with its own 
    backbone element:
    
    1. indication      -> indication.diseaseSymptomProcedure, .intendedEffect, .otherTherapy
    2. contraindication -> contraindication.diseaseSymptomProcedure, .otherTherapy
    3. interaction      -> interaction.interactant, .type, .effect, .incidence, .management
    4. undesirable-effect -> undesirableEffect.symptomConditionEffect, .classification, .frequencyOfOccurrence
    5. warning          -> warning.code
    
    Each type has a dedicated ePI profile with specific constraints.
  -->

